\title{Labeled chunk names:\\
  classifying chunks whose names are not filenames}
\author{Daniel Bosk}
\begin{document}
\maketitle

@ \section{Introduction}

This example is a companion to [[embedded.nw]].  There a chunk's
language is imposed by \emph{where it is used}; here it is imposed by
\emph{what its name is told to mean}.  The case is common in test-driven
literate programs: a module lives in a chunk named for its file, like
[[greet.py]], and its tests live in a sibling chunk whose name carries a
label in front of the same file reference.  Such a name is not itself a
filename, so [[autolang]] cannot guess its language---and deliberately
does not try, because the guess would often be wrong: a chunk that
\emph{references} [[greet.py]] may be Python that imports it or a shell
script that runs it.

The remedy is a rule.  [[noweave]]'s [[-langrule]] option (the
[[re:regex=lexer]] form of [[autolang]], described in [[tominted.nw]])
labels every chunk whose name matches a regular expression.  Because the
regex is matched against the \emph{whole} chunk name, the label in front
of the file reference is what the rule keys on---so two chunks that embed
the same [[greet.py]] can be classified differently:

\begin{description}
\item[The module] [[greet.py]] is a filename, so it needs no rule:
  [[autolang]] reads it as [[python]] from the name.
\item[The unit test] a chunk labeled \emph{test} is Python (it imports
  the module and asserts), classified by a rule mapping that label to
  [[python]].
\item[The smoke check] a chunk labeled \emph{check} is a POSIX shell
  script (it runs the module and inspects the output), classified by a
  second rule mapping \emph{that} label to [[bash]].
\end{description}

The pay-off is again in the index: with each chunk labeled,
[[autodefs.python3]] scans the module and the test, [[autodefs.sh]]
scans the shell check, and neither claims the other's identifiers.
Without the rules the test and the check would be unlabeled, every
[[autodefs]] filter would scan them, and [[autodefs.make]] could even
read a Python [[for]] line as a Makefile rule.

\section{The module}

[[greet.py]] is an ordinary root chunk named for its file, so its
language follows from the name with no rule at all.

<<[[greet.py]]>>=
def greet(name):
    """Return a greeting addressed to ``name``."""
    return f"hello, {name}"
@

\section{The unit test}

The test imports the module and checks one example.  Its chunk name,
\emph{test} followed by the quoted file reference, is not a filename, so
the weave is told to treat names of that shape as Python.  The rule is
\begin{verbatim}
-langrule 'test \[\[.*\.py\]\]=python'
\end{verbatim}
and with it [[autodefs.python3]] indexes the test function below.

<<test [[greet.py]]>>=
from greet import greet


def test_greet_uses_the_name():
    assert greet("world") == "hello, world"
@

\section{The smoke check}

The smoke check runs the module through the interpreter and inspects
the output---a shell task, even though it mentions the same Python file.
This is why the language cannot be read off the embedded [[greet.py]]:
the chunk is shell, not Python.  Nor does it carry a [[#!]] line for
[[autolang]] to read (that would be the shebang case of [[embedded.nw]]);
the label is the only signal, so a second rule keyed on \emph{check}
supplies the language:
\begin{verbatim}
-langrule 'check \[\[.*\.py\]\]=bash'
\end{verbatim}

<<check [[greet.py]]>>=
# Run the module and confirm it greets as expected.
out=$(python3 -c 'from greet import greet; print(greet("noweb"))')
case $out in
  "hello, noweb") echo "ok" ;;
  *) echo "FAIL: got '$out'" >&2; exit 1 ;;
esac
@

\section{Building this document}

A single highlighted, indexed weave applies both rules and stacks the
two relevant scanners.  [[-langrule]] implies [[-autolang]] and may be
repeated:
\begin{verbatim}
noweave -delay -autolang \
    -langrule 'test \[\[.*\.py\]\]=python' \
    -langrule 'check \[\[.*\.py\]\]=bash' \
    -autodefs python3 -autodefs sh -index \
    -filter 'tominted -lexer noweb_lexer.py' \
    labeled.nw > labeled.tex
pdflatex -shell-escape labeled.tex
\end{verbatim}
The highlighted build needs the one-time [[latexminted]] setup
described in [[README.python]].  Drop both [[-langrule]] options to see
the default behaviour: the test and check chunks weave unhighlighted,
because a labeled name carries no language on its own.

